The spherically shaped CDs (1 to 5 nm) were fully characterized in our previous research articles [17,18]. The EDX, XRD and Raman spectral analysis were also described there [11,12] which confirmed thesynthesis of amorphous CDs with the presence of C and O. The CDs were further functionalized with FA and loaded with rutin. The as-formed FA conjugated and rutin loaded CDs were analyzed by TEM (Fig. 1a
                        ) which showed nearly spherically shaped particleswith average diameter of 70 nm, and the hydrodynamic size was increased to 322.4 ± 9.34 nm upon FA attachment and drug loading (Fig. 1b). On the other hand, CDs showed the hydrodynamic size value of only 13.71 ± 1.13 nm (Fig. 1b). The FTIR spectrum (Fig. 1c) of CDs displayed the key bands /peaks at 3327 cm−1, 2935 cm−1, 1596–1700 cm−1 and 1021 cm−1 due to OH stretching, CH stretching, aromatic C=C/ CO stretching and CO stretching respectively [22]. FA and RUT showed several charactericstics transmittance peaks. FA showed a typical CO stretching peak at 1697 cm−1. Bare rutin displayed peaks at 1667 cm−1, 1501 cm−1 and 1361 cm−1 due to CO stretching, aromatic CC stretching and CO stretching respectively. However, the transmittance peaks of CDs were changed upon FA and rutin conjugation. The UV–Vis spectrum of CDs displayed peaks at 285 nm, 340 nm and 370 nm. FA displayed the peaks at 285 nm and 350 nm, whereas rutin displayed the peaks at 255 nm and 350 nm. However, the original peak positions of CDs, FA and rutin were changed/shifted upon conjugation (Fig. 2a).DLC and DEE were calculated by using UV–Vis spectroscopic techniques (Table 1
                        ) and the values were found to be approximately 14.5 and 16.96 % respectively. The pH-dependent (pH = 5.5 & 7.4) drug/rutin release from the nanohybrids was also evaluated at different time intervals (Fig. 2b). After 48 h, the drug concentration was around 1.65 μg/mL & 1.86 μg/mL at pH = 7.4 and pH = 5.5 respectively, indicating higher drug release at lower pH.

We have also investigated weather FA-CDs-RUT could retard the migration of breast cancer cells cells along with apoptosis via both wound healing and transwell migration assays (
                        Fig. 4b and 5

                        ). We found that FA-CDs-RUT significantly reduced the migration of MCF-7 cells at a concentration of 50 μg/mL under both the assay conditions. These finding highlighted that FA-CDs-RUT exhibit anti-apoptotic nature along with anti-migratory property.
